<title>The son of the Wind</title>
<summary><i>The Son of the Wind. By |han≠kass’o (L VIII.-8. 6687-6708). </i>|na ka ti&apos;s mother tells him not to say the name of the son of the Wind until his father has made a hut for them. When the father is finished, |na ka ti calls the Wind&apos;s name and then runs to the hut. The Wind blows away the people&apos;s houses, except for the Wind&apos;s hut. The Wind&apos;s mother picks up the son of the Wind and it stops blowing. A strong shelter must be made before calling the Wind&apos;s name.</summary><comments>1) A page inserted between the front cover and frontispiece of Book VIII-8 features a number (III) and a list of dates in chronological order, with |han≠kass&apos;o&apos;s movements (before coming to Mowbray) noted alongside, 2) p.6687opp: |han≠kass&apos;o heard this from his mother (|xabbi-an), and a note on her parents and their names; about ||<i>kuarri</i>, 3) p.6687v: see <i>The porcupine eats ||kuarri, </i>4) 6688v: see <i>Locusts or ||kabba- |kha</i>, 5) p.6694v: see <i>The Wind</i>, 6) p.6706v: a word for a dry stream-bed in |xam and Dutch, 7) See also <i>The Wind </i>and <i>Notes to the story of The Wind</i>, 8) This story is found in Book VIII-8 </comments><date>15 April 1878 (started)</date><storypages>6687-6708</storypages><category>History (Early Race)</category><author>|han≠kass'o (Klein Jantje) (VIII)</author><keyword><kw>Wind</kw><subkw>the son of the Wind</subkw></keyword>
